class Solution:
    def getCommon(self, nums1: List[int], nums2: List[int]) -> int:
        i = j = 0
        while i < len(nums1) and j < len(nums2):
            if nums1[i] == nums2[j]:
                return nums1[i]
            elif nums1[i] < nums2[j]:
                i += 1
            else:
                j += 1
        return -1

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
Since both arrays are sorted in non-decreasing order, we can use a two-pointer technique to find the smallest common element efficiently in O(n + m) time.

Initialize two pointers i and j at the start of nums1 and nums2 respectively.
While both pointers are within bounds:
- If nums1[i] == nums2[j], we have found a common element. Because we traverse from left to right, this is guaranteed to be the smallest common element; return it immediately.
- If nums1[i] < nums2[j], increment i (the current element in nums1 cannot be in nums2 or any later element of nums2 would be even larger).
- Otherwise, increment j.

If the loops terminate without finding a match, no common element exists; return -1.

This approach correctly handles duplicates (it returns the first occurrence of a common value) and meets the O(n + m) time requirement with O(1) extra space.

Time Complexity: O(n + m)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
